sndlib.core.problem
Class SolvedProblem

java.lang.Object
  sndlib.core.problem.Problem
      sndlib.core.problem.SolvedProblem

public class SolvedProblem
extends Problem

This class connects a specific Solution to a network design Problem.

It provides methods to check the consistency of the solution with the problem and to compute the routing paths and flow values derived from that solution.

Author:
Roman Klaehne
See Also:
Solution, Problem, RoutingPath, DemandFlow, LinkFlow

getDemandPathFlow

public DemandPathFlow getDemandPathFlow(Demand demand,
                                        java.util.List<java.lang.String> path,
                                        OperatingState state)
Returns the total flow on the given path which is incurred by the specified demand when the network is in the given state.

Paths are compared with respect to the link model. If the link model is UNDIRECTED the direction into which the path is traversed is not taken into account.

Parameters:
demand - the demand
path - the path for which the flow value is determined
state - the operating state
Returns:
the total flow on the given path which is incurred by the specified demand in the given state

computeFlowsAndPaths

public void computeFlowsAndPaths()
                          throws java.lang.IllegalStateException
Initiates the computation of all routing paths, link flows and demand flows.
The results will be cached for later calls to the corresponding supply methods.

If the underlying solution and problem are not consistent with each other, an IllegalStateException is thrown.

Throws:
java.lang.IllegalStateException - if the underlying solution and problem are not consistent with each other
See Also:
getDemandFlow(Demand, OperatingState), getLinkFlow(Link, OperatingState), getRoutingPath(FlowPath)

isConsistent

public boolean isConsistent()
Tests whether the underlying solution and problem are consistent with each other.

This method is equivalent to checkConsistency().size() == 0.

Returns:
true if and only if the underlying solution and problem are consistent to each other; false otherwise

checkConsistency

public com.atesio.utils.message.Messages checkConsistency()
Checks whether the underlying solution and problem are consistent with each other.

If the returned messages are empty then the solution is consistent with the problem (see isConsistent()).
If an consisency error occurs then all the cached routing paths and flows will be released.

Note: This is no check for solution feasibility! For doing this use SolutionValidators.

Returns:
the error messages indicating where the consistency is violated
